{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Affirmative action is standardly pursued in relation to admissions to prestigious universities, in hiring for prestigious jobs, and when it comes to being elected to parliament.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "A good is competitive when, if we improve A's chances of getting the good, we reduce B's chances of obtaining the good.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "I argue that some of the most prominent objections against affirmative action-in particular, the reverse discrimination objection and the merit objection-speak less against Non-competitive Affirmative Action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "And that some of the most prominent arguments in favor of affirmative action, insofar as they justify Competitive Affirmative Action, also justify Non-competitive Affirmative Action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "A good is non-competitive when, if we improve A's chances of obtaining the good, we do not reduce B's chances of obtaining the good.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "It is surprising that this distinction-between Competitive and Non-competitive Affirmative Action-has not been acknowledged before, at least for three reasons.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "First, we should expect that the injustices which affect members of disadvantaged groups when it comes to receiving competitive goods-such as places at prestigious universities and jobs-also affect them when it comes to receiving non-competitive goods, such as being granted early parole or being free from arbitrary arrest.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Second, which forms of affirmative action we have in mind may make a difference when it comes to justifying affirmative action.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Third, the distinction is also of practical importance.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "If I am right, it will often be easier to justify Non-competitive Affirmative Action than Competitive Affirmative Action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Affirmative action is objectionable, according to this objection, because it amounts to racial or sexual discrimination against the majority candidate.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "But Non-Competitive Affirmative Action seems relevantly different in this respect.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Take the parole case again. If we pursue affirmative action in relation to the black person applying for parole, we do not lower the chances of the white person being granted parole.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The reverse discrimination objection has less force against Non-competitive Affirmative Action precisely because this form of affirmative action has to do with non-competitive goods.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "According to this objection, affirmative action is objectionable because it clashes with the meritocratic principle that the best qualified candidate be selected.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Whatever the merits of this merit objection, it does not have the same force against Non-competitive Affirmative Action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "When it comes to Non-competitive Affirmative Action, majority and minority candidates are not pitted against each other: they are not fighting for the same goods.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "The merit objection does not seem to threaten Non-competitive Affirmative Action in the same way that it threatens Competitive Affirmative Action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "The injustice has, in many cases, resulted in a lack of both competitive goods (e.g., jobs, places at universities, seats in parliament) and non-competitive goods (e.g., early parole, freedom from arbitrary arrest, self-respect).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "If Competitive Affirmative Action is required as compensation for past injustice, Non-competitive Affirmative Action is also required as compensation for past injustice.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
